Quarto websites do not use Jekyll, so we need to disable it and make sure the correct GitHub Actions workflow is set up.

🧭 Step-by-Step Solution

STEP 1 — Disable Jekyll

You must tell GitHub Pages not to use Jekyll.

  1. In your Quarto project folder (the root of your repo), create a new file named:

    .nojekyll

    ⚠️ Important: There is no file extension — the name is exactly .nojekyll

  2. Add and push the file to GitHub:

    bash
    git add .nojekyll
git commit -m "Disable Jekyll for Quarto build"
git push origin main

STEP 2 — Verify your Quarto project settings

Check your _quarto.yml file. It should include this (or similar):

yaml
project:
  type: website
  output-dir: _site

This ensures Quarto builds your site to the _site folder, which GitHub Pages expects.

STEP 3 — Update your GitHub Actions workflow

If your repository has a workflow file under
.github/workflows/
(for example: .github/workflows/publish.yml or .github/workflows/pages.yml),
replace its content with this Quarto-compatible version:

yaml
name: Quarto Publish

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Check out repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Setup Quarto
        uses: quarto-dev/quarto-actions/setup@v2

      - name: Render site
        run: quarto render

      - name: Publish to GitHub Pages
        uses: quarto-dev/quarto-actions/publish@v2
        with:
          target: gh-pages
        env:
          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}

Then push it:

bash
git add .github/workflows/publish.yml
git commit -m "Fix GitHub Actions for Quarto site"
git push origin main

STEP 4 — Rebuild & Redeploy

Once pushed, GitHub will automatically start a new workflow run:

  • Go to your repo → Actions tab.

  • You should see the workflow running again.

  • Wait until it shows ✅ Success.

STEP 5 — Check GitHub Pages settings

Finally, go to:

  • Settings → Pages

  • Under Build and Deployment, make sure:

    • Source = “GitHub Actions”

    • Branch = gh-pages (if that’s what your workflow publishes to)

Once this is done, your Quarto site should deploy successfully 🎉

❌ Root Cause

The error says:

vbnet
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'nbformat'
Jupyter is not available in this Python installation.
Install with python3 -m pip install jupyter

That means when GitHub Actions tries to render your Quarto site, it can’t find Jupyter — which Quarto needs to render .qmd notebooks containing Python code.

So, Quarto is failing at the Render site step.

✅ How to Fix It

You need to install Jupyter (and nbformat) inside your GitHub Actions workflow before rendering your site.

Here’s exactly what to do:

Step 1. Edit your workflow file

Open the file .github/workflows/publish.yml in your repo and add this step right after “Set up Quarto” and before “Render site”.

Your updated file should look like this:

yaml
name: Quarto Publish

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Check out repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Set up Quarto
        uses: quarto-dev/quarto-actions/setup@v2

      # 🟢 ADD THIS STEP
      - name: Install Jupyter
        run: |
          python3 -m pip install jupyter nbformat

      - name: Render site
        run: quarto render

      - name: Publish to GitHub Pages
        uses: quarto-dev/quarto-actions/publish@v2
        with:
          target: gh-pages
        env:
          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}

Step 2. Commit and push the changes

bash
git add .github/workflows/publish.yml
git commit -m "Fix: install Jupyter before rendering Quarto site"
git push origin main

Step 3. Re-run the workflow

  1. Go to Actions → Quarto Publish

  2. You’ll see a new workflow run start automatically.

  3. Wait for it to reach ✅ “Success”.
